This is **not** proof that $H_0$ is false. **High evidence against** $H_0$ leads to rejection. Because: If the true expected value is $25.0$, samples with $\overline Y\geq 25.718$ will only occur with a probability of $5\%$.

Decision rule: Reject $H_0$ if $\overline Y\geq 25.718$.


The following key figure is also interesting: Assuming that $H_0$ holds, what is the probability - if the experiment is repeated - of obtaining a result that is at least as extreme as the one observed?
This key figure is called the **$p$ value** and is calculated as follows:

\begin{equation*}
        \mathbb P(\overline Y_{\text{Rep.}}\geq \overline Y|H_0)
        = \mathbb P(\overline Y_{\text{Rep.}} \geq 26.3|\mu=25.0)
        = 0.0015 = 0.15%.
\end{equation*}


